review_blob: Cask, Market Porter, 17/5/08.  Dark copper coloured with a fruity nose, mostly sweet toffee malt and a little hop aroma.  Not a lot going on.

Cask, Market Porter, 17/5/08, Poured a nice clean, clear copper colour with a thin white head.  Toffee and a noticeable hoppy aroma, with a sweet malt and grassy hop taste.  Not particularly exciting.
Cask, Market Porter 17/5/08, Copper coloured and clear with a thin white head.  Some caramel notes.  Some fruity and grassy hops balance out the malty taste.
Basically a dumbed-down, mass produced ale.  No outstanding flavour, besides a slight bit of breadiness.  Even the colour of this beer is near water.

Bottle and tap, both with the trademark Coopers cloudiness (wish more beers werent so scared of being served the way God intended, with the yeast).  Highly carbed, with a dry, malty taste, with a candy sweetness.  Very complex, especially from older, cellared bottles.
Nice stout, well balanced with dry roast and bitter finish over a smooth, well bodied beer.

Cask at The Eagle, Ravenscourt Park.  A lot more golden coloured than I expected, very sweet and a reasonable amount of bittering hops, although not particularly well balanced.  A strong citric aftertaste was a little off putting after a couple.
A beautiful complex beer of with a balanced sweetness, warming alcohol and heady aroma of dried fruits with a slight bready taste of the yeast coming through.

Bottle.  Poured well and looked attractive, coal black and a light tan head.  The aroma was sulphur and wet cardboard.  The taste was thin, watery, with a bit of roast and caramel.  Not particularly satisfying.
Overwhelming sweetness with hints of liquorice and cherries.  Presents well in a glass, a deep rich amber colour.  Nice to sip away on a cold night.

Cask conditioned from the Rose and Crown, Sandhurst.  Smooth, low bittered ale with slight floral hop aroma.   Nice mouth feel and body, but lacking anything distinctive.  Interesting concept from a brewery that is breaking new ground.
Cask conditioned from the Rose and Crown, Sandhurst.  Brilliant tasting stout, smooth silky taste well balanced with a bitter, roast taste.  Very full bodied and warming.  Lovely.
